==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extravasate
<hw>Ex*trav"a*sate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Extravasated</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Extravasating</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>extra-</ets> + L. <ets>vas</ets> vessel: cf. F.
<ets>extravaser</ets>. See <er>Vase</er>.]</ety> <def>To force or let
out of the proper vessels or arteries, as blood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extravasate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Extravasate
<hw>Ex*trav"a*sate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Extravasate</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>
<def>To pass by infiltration or effusion from the normal channel, such
as a blood vessel or a lymphatic, into the surrounding tissue; -- said
of blood, lymph, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extravasation</ent>⟦br⟧
